text.i: Bark Street-Buffington Street-Stevens Road Intersection Study, Swansea
Introduction
Existing Conditions

page.text: The town of Swansea requested SRPEDD’s assistance in the evaluation of the
intersection of Bark Street, Buffington Street and Stevens Road in the northeast
portion of the town. This particular intersection was studied by SRPEDD in
2005 for a signal warrants analysis to determine if traffic signals could be
installed to mitigate traffic congestion and safety problems. Although the
evaluation concluded that the intersection does warrant a traffic signal, the
recommendations from SRPEDD suggested an alternative improvement that
would include a roundabout. The study also pointed out that the existing
geometry that forms the current intersection does not lend itself for the
installation of a roundabout without considerable land takings.
SRPEDD revisited this location to determine if this location still meets signal
warrants and to assist the town in considering the alternative of implementing a
The intersection of Bark Street, Buffington Street and Stevens Road is a four
legged, unsignalized intersection located at the north eastern edge of Swansea.
The area surrounding the intersection is primarily residential with some town
offices nearby. This includes the Swansea Planning Department, Animal
Control facility and Town conservation farm located immediately west of the
intersection. The intersection also connects to Route 138 in Somerset to the
east, and Route 6 as well as Route I-195 to the south.
Bark Street is a north/south running, two lane roadway with a posted speed
limit of 35 miles per hour (MPH). South of the intersection, the road is classified
as an urban minor arterial road with a 30 foot wide pavement width and an
Average Daily Traffic volume (ADT) of 6,300 vehicles per day. In addition to
Route 6 and I-195, Bark Street provides connections to several residential areas
the Somerset Middle School and Read Street within the town of Somerset.
North of the intersection, Bark Street is a two lane urban collector road with
a 35 foot pavement width and an ADT of 5,000 vehicles per day. Bark Street
provides connections to the residential neighborhoods along Chace Street and
Marvel Street. Bark Street is a designated bicycle route from the intersection
north to Marvel Street, with signage and a 4 foot striped bicycle lane to the
north and 6ft to the south. These bicycle lanes were installed in the 1990’s and
Southeastern Regional Planning and Economic Development District
Stevens Road and Buffington Street are the east/west running roads that are
both classified as urban minor arterials. Stevens Road, located to the west of
the intersection, is a two lane, 30-foot wide road with no traffic control. It
has a posted speed limit of 35 MPH, and an ADT of 4,500 vehicles per day. It
connects to residential neighborhoods as well as the Swansea public schools
of Joseph Case Jr. High, Joseph Case High, and Elizabeth S. Brown Elementary
schools. These schools are located near the intersection of Stevens Road and
Hortonville Road/Gardner’s Neck Road. The entire length of Stevens Road is a
designated bicycle route with a 2 foot wide striped bicycle shoulder and bicycle
route signage. Due to the width of the bicycle shoulder, bicycle and directional
pavement markings would not be appropriate. The bicycle lanes on Stevens
Road provide a direct connection to the South Coast Bikeway Route through
lack bicycle and directional pavement markings required under the current
guidance of the Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices (MUTCD). Figure
1 displays examples of pavement markings for bicycle lanes under the current
MUTCD. South of the intersection, there is a shared bicycle/breakdown lane
that is not a designated or signed bicycle route. Bicycle lanes are proposed for
the section south of the intersection as outlined in SRPEDD’s 2012 Regional
Transportation Plan. Both approaches on Bark Street to Stevens Road and
Buffington Street are controlled with stop signs.

page.text: Buffington Street is located east of the intersection and is a two lane, 30-foot
wide roadway with no traffic control at the intersection. The road has a posted
speed limit of 35 MPH and an ADT of 6,300 vehicles per day. Buffington Street
It connects to residential neighborhoods and Buffington Park in addition to
providing a major connection to Route 138 and downtown Somerset. There
are sections of sidewalk on the northwest corner of the intersection and the
interiors of the two interior triangles as shown in Figure 2. Crosswalks are striped
on the Bark Street southbound and northbound approaches, the Buffington
Street ramp to Bark Street approach, the Buffington Street westbound approach
and both ends of the Stephens Road to Bark Street ramp.
Automatic Traffic Recorders (ATRs) were placed at each approach to the
intersection to collect 24-hour volume, speed and classification data. The results
from the ATRs are displayed in Table 1 on the next page. The majority of the
traffic is made up of passenger cars and heavy truck traffic is 1% or less of the
composition of the roadway traffic. The 85th percentile speed is the speed at
which 85% of vehicles are traveling at or below, and is typically used to set speed
limits. The 85th percentile speed data collected indicates that the majority of
traffic is traveling well above, 4 – 9 miles per hour faster than the posted 35 mile
per hour speed limit on all approaches.

Turning movement counts were conducted at the intersection for the AM and
PM peak hours, the hours when the volume of traffic is typically at its highest.
This data was used to calculate the existing level of service at the intersection
using techniques defined in the Highway Capacity Manual and Synchro software.
Level of service is a measure of vehicle congestion at an intersection and is
presented through a rating of A through F. LOS A represents uncongested
conditions and minimal vehicle delays while LOS F represents gridlocked
conditions with excessive vehicle delays. A visualization of LOS A-F is shown in

page.text: The total volume for the AM Peak Hour (7:15-8:15) was 892 vehicles and the
total volume for the PM peak hour (4:15-5:15) was 1,285 vehicles. The analysis
based on these volumes for unsignalized intersections results in a LOS C for the
AM Peak Hour and a LOS F for the PM Peak.
An analysis of future conditions at the intersection was performed using data
from SRPEDD’s Travel Demand Model. A growth rate of 0.5% was used to predict
traffic volumes for the year 2035. A comparison of 2012 traffic volumes and
forecasted 2035 volumes for the PM Peak hour is shown in Table 2.
To determine if there is a significant crash problem at the intersection, the
Equivalent Property Damage Only (EPDO) and the Accidents per Million Entering
Using an EPDO index allows intersections to be ranked based on the severity of
collisions. A point system is applied to the crashes based on the severity of the
crash (property damage only, personal injury, or where a fatality occurred). An
EPDO rate exceeding 17.7 (the regional average) is considered unacceptable
in the SRPEDD area. Calculations indicate that the EPDO crash rate for the
intersection is 28.33, which is considered unacceptable as it is above the
ACC/MEV is a calculated crash rate that compares vehicle crashes to the volume
of traffic at a given intersection. Where locations have higher crash rates, it is
considered to have greater danger. It provides a comparison of intersections
with different traffic characteristics, ultimately providing a probability of being in
a collision at a given intersection; the higher the rate, the greater the danger. An
ACC/MEV crash rate for unsignalized intersections exceeding 0.58 is considered
unacceptable in the SRPEDD region. Calculations indicate that the ACC/MEV
crash rate for the intersections 2.06, which exceeds the regional average and
identifies this intersection as a safety problem. The calculated rates and regional
average rates are displayed in Table 3.
Crash reports were provided by the Swansea Police Department for a three year
period between 2009-2011. During this span, a total of 29 crashes occurred at
the intersection, 13 of which resulted in injury. There were fourteen rear-end
type crashes, fourteen angle crashes, and one head-on collision. Table 4 shows
the details of each of these crashes, while the location of the crashes is shown in

page.text: Analysis of the crash data shows a high incidence of rear-end and right angle
crashes, demonstrating that the current two-way stop controlled configuration
does not provide for safe passage through the intersection. The majority of
these types of crashes were attributed to operating in a reckless, negligent or
aggressive manner, following too closely or failure to yield right-of-way based on
the crash reports. The frequency of these types of crashes, combined with the
attributed causes and the high rate of speed indicates that speeding could be a
contributing problem at this location. This is verified with the traffic count data
where the 85th percentile speeds exceed the current posted speed limit of 35
mph on Stevens Road and Buffington Street. These rear-end crashes could be

due to the inability to properly judge vehicle speeds approaching from Stevens
Road and Buffington Street due to limited sight distance. Another contributing
factor might include a motorist’s impatience over a long delay when turning.
According to the 2006 Massachusetts Highway Department Project Development
and Design Guide which contains elements from “A Policy on Geometric Design
of Highways and Streets” by the American Association of State Highway and
Transportation Officials (AASHTO)(2004), intersection sight distance should be
sufficient ”to allow drivers to perceive the presence of potentially conflicting
vehicles.” The intent of an intersection having proper sight distance allows
motorists enough distance and time to safely determine and maneuver a vehicle
to avoid dangerous collisions. The design speed on the major road contributes to
the required intersection sight distance at the minor road.
The necessary sight distance required to safely turn from Bark Street on either
side of the intersection should be a minimum of 390 feet for left turns and a
minimum of 335 feet for right turns and through movements. This distance
allows motorists to judge, decide and execute a safe turning maneuver.
Based on field measurements shown in Figure 5, the existing sight distance
for northbound vehicles on Bark Street looking towards Buffington Street is
approximately 200 feet. This does not meet the minimum requirement for left
turns, right turns and through movements at the intersection. The motorist’s
view of Buffington Street is obscured by trees shown in Figure 65 located in the

text.i: Improvement Alternatives

page.text: To address the transportation issues identified, several alternatives were
considered to improve the intersection. These alternatives include:
two scenarios involving a roundabout and a “T” intersection,
The No Build scenario simply keeps the intersection in its current layout as a
two-way stop controlled intersection and is used as a control scenario. With no
proposed improvements, the current level of service would degrade over time
as traffic rates increase. Analyses of future conditions show that the level of
service will remain at a LOS F.
The 2005 Intersection Traffic Control Warrants Analysis indicated the intersection
met the warrants for a change from the current two way stop controlled
intersection to an all-way stop controlled intersection. The 2005 analysis also
stated that significant modifications to the intersection would be necessary to
achieve an improved measure of safety due to inadequate sight distance.
Based on volume and classification, this intersection would be an ideal location
for a single lane “modern” roundabout. Modern roundabouts have proven to be
very effective in controlling traffic flow in a safe and efficient manner. A properly
designed roundabout can offer operational and safety benefits that exceed those
offered by traffic signals or stop signs and can provide effective traffic calming to
slow the average speed of travel.
The Massachusetts Highway Design Guide 2006 Edition governs the design of
roundabouts. Based on the current functional classification of the roadway, the
Massachusetts Highway Design Guide recommends a total diameter of 100-
130 for a single lane roundabout, with 55-95 feet for a center island, 5-10 feet
for a truck apron, and 29-35 for circulating traffic. Due to right of way and land
use constraints, a center island with of 65 feet, a 5 foot truck apron and a 30
foot travel lane was used for this scenario, for a total diameter of 100 feet. The
Highway Design Guide for single lane roundabouts is shown in Figure 8 on the
The minor arterial classification for the roads at this intersection necessitates the
100-130 foot diameter roundabout. However, traffic volume ranges from 4500 to
6000 vehicles per day with approximately 1% of that traffic consisting of heavy
trucks. This suggests that these roads are more consistent with traffic conditions
observed on collector roads. Under these conditions, the town might consider a
smaller diameter roundabout of 80 to 100 feet for the center of the intersection.
This option requires review by an engineer in conjunction with MassDOT.

Replacing the existing intersection with a roundabout as shown in Figure 9
would improve the operation from a LOS F to LOS B and would decrease the
excessive delay at the intersection to an average of 10.5 seconds. An analysis of
future conditions forecasts that this scenario would operate at an overall LOS B
with an average 12.8 seconds of delay in the year 2035.
In addition to improvements to current and anticipated traffic operations, the
roundabout also offers a measure of traffic calming specifically to Buffington
Street and Stevens Road. Motorists traveling on these roads would be forced
to reduce their vehicle speeds to obey traffic controls (Yield signs) and safely
navigate through the roundabout. In theory, this could result in a reduction of
crashes, but most certainly result in a reduction of crashes that result in an injury

Justifying the need for the installation of a traffic signal is based on a series of
thresholds using traffic volume and crash data. These thresholds are referred
to as warrants as defined in the Manual for Uniform Traffic Control Devices
(MUTCD). MUTCD is the definitive national authority on the design, placement
and use of all traffic controls. The proper use of traffic controls in a formally
accepted and uniform fashion eliminates unnecessary, inappropriate, ineffective,
and confusing traffic controls. A warrants analysis is generally the first step
in determining the need for, and ultimately the installation of traffic control
In 2005, the Signal Warrants Analysis determined the intersection meets five
In 2012, a Signal Warrants Analysis determined the intersection continues to
meet the warrants for consideration of signalization. The analysis also indicates
that the intersection meets the warrants pertaining to vehicle crashes. Crash

at the intersection with 5 crashes correctable with a traffic signal. Between 2009
thru 2011, the intersection averaged 5 crashes per year that are correctable by

text.i: Conclusion and Recommendations

page.text: the current LOS from F to B. while an analysis of a signal under future traffic
conditions is projected to operate at LOS A in the AM peak hour and LOS B in the
PM peak hour. A summary of PM Peak LOS and estimated delay for current and
future volumes for each alternative is shown in Table 5.
Based on the current and future volumes along with the constraints with the
existing layout of the intersection, it is recommended that the town pursue
Alternative 3B - Roundabout on the east, T-intersection on the west, or
Alternative 4 - installation of a signalized intersection.
The roundabout alternative is expected to improve the overall level of service
from LOS F to B. The roundabout also provides an element of traffic calming to
vehicles traveling on Buffington Street and Stevens Road. A roundabout with
appropriate signage will force motor vehicles to reduce their travel speed in
order to safely traverse the circle. Because this measure forces motor vehicles
to operate at slower speeds, it also improves safe passage for pedestrians and
The installation of a traffic signal at the intersection is expected to improve the
overall LOS from F to B and provide safety for pedestrians and bicyclists as part
of the operational phasing. Although the traffic signal provides similar results in
improved operation and safety, the difference between these two improvements
is implementation costs and how the improvement fits in with the character of
the surrounding neighborhood. The USDOT’s Federal Highway Administration
(FHWA) has identified modern roundabout intersections as one of nine proven
life-saving roadway safety strategies. Modern roundabouts are not only safer

text.i: Table 5:
Synchro Analysis
Bark Street-Buffington Street-Stevens Road Intersection Study, Swansea

page.text: than traditional signalized and stop-controlled intersections, where appropriate
and properly designed, roundabouts operate more efficiently, often have lower
life cycle costs, and result in increased fuel efficiency.
Unlike other types of intersections, roundabouts are designed to slow the
speed of vehicles entering by deflecting them from a straight-line path into the
roundabout. Roundabouts eliminate dangerous left turns across opposing traffic
lanes and virtually eliminate high-speed right-angle and head-on crashes.
While initial construction costs can be higher with roundabouts, they often
have lower operating and maintenance costs than signalized intersections.
Roundabouts can have ongoing costs for lighting and maintaining the
landscaping, but unlike a signalized intersection, there is no signal equipment
to install, power, and maintain. Roundabouts have longer service lives than
traditional intersections resulting in better economic value over the long term,
especially when you factor in the reduction of fatal and injury crashes.
Roundabouts are also a “green” alternative for intersections and not just for
their aesthetic appeal. Reduced vehicle idling means fewer emissions and less
wasted fuel. Less acceleration and fewer sudden “hard stops” means quieter,
more peaceful transportation through communities. Landscaping in the central
island, splitter islands, and along the approaches can further benefit and
As with either improvement alternative, projects using state and federal funds
must include pedestrian and bicycle accommodations as part of the MassDOT
Healthy Transportation Initiative. This includes sidewalks, crosswalks, and
bicycle lanes that are in compliance with the MUTCD and ADA guidelines. The
intersection is currently part of a designated bicycle route and implementation
of any of the recommendations must maintain or enhance safe bicycle flows.
Furthermore, with evidence of speeding, particularly on Stevens Road and
Buffington Street, it is recommended that a targeted speed enforcement
campaign be conducted. Greater police presence will decrease vehicle speeds
in the short term and give this location the perception as being considered a
